            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dahlia Sharma is a product of a San Francisco that feels both distant and immediate. Born in the Sunset District to a Punjabi immigrant father who drove a taxi and an Irish-American mother who worked as a seamstress, her childhood was a vibrant mix of aromas\u2014cardamom chai and Irish stew\u2014and the constant hum of a city in flux. Her parents\u2019 love story was one of quiet resilience, a bond formed over shared experiences as outsiders in their own ways.\n\nDahlia\u2019s path diverged from her peers after she graduated from high school. While they filed college applications, she felt the pull of the city\u2019s electric nightlife. She took a job as a barback in a classic North Beach establishment, captivated by the choreographed chaos behind the bar and the theater of human connection in front of it. She found her university not in a lecture hall, but under the tutelage of a grizzled, old-school bartender who taught her the chemistry of spirits, the history of a perfect Manhattan, and the art of listening.\n\nHer career became her craft. Dahlia ascended from dive bars to upscale hotel lounges, earning a reputation for her precision, unflappable calm, and an almost psychic ability to know what a customer needed. A key turning point was a decade-long relationship with a jazz musician, a romance that filled her twenties and thirties with smoky clubs and late-night talks but ultimately ended amicably, leaving her with beautiful memories and a fierce self-reliance.\n\nNow, at 53, Dahlia is the Lead Bartender at a renowned cocktail bar in Hayes Valley, a position that affords her a comfortable life. She lives in a rent-controlled apartment she\u2019s had for twenty years, just a 0.8-mile walk from work. Her daily routine is a ritual: a morning walk to a local caf\u00e9, afternoons reading in Patricia's Green, and evenings orchestrating the flow of her bar. Her social life is a rich tapestry woven from loyal regulars and the younger bartenders she now mentors. Her dream is no longer about ambition, but about legacy\u2014passing on her craft and ensuring the art of true hospitality endures. Dahlia is a cornerstone of her community, a quiet institution as integral to her corner of San Francisco as the fog rolling in over the hills."
        },
